Effect of forest condition on Pacific giant salamander populations

Allison Hacker and Cameryn Brock

11/20/2019

Introduction

The Pacific giant salamander (Dicamptodon tenebrosus) is the largest amphibian species in the Pacific Northwest (Figure 1). Although not a threatened species, it is sensitive because it relies on cold, clean stream habitat for food and reproduction (Pacific Giant Salamander n.d.). Logging threatens this habitat by removing canopy cover and increasing soil erosion, which results in warmer water and increased suspended sediment. Due to their sensitivity to such environmental changes, amphibian populations can be used as an indicator of riparian ecosystem health (Welsh and Ollivier, 1998). Pacific giant salamander populations have been monitored in both clear cut and intact old growth forest in Oregon States H.J. Andrews Experimental Forest since 1993. In this study, we compare salamander abundance and weight in the two forest sections and various channel types to explore the effect of logging on salamander populations.

Figure 1. Pacific giant salamander (Dicamptodon tenebrosus). Credit: Jeffery Marsten Wikimedia

Data and methods

Pacific giant salamander data were provided by the Aquatic Vertebrate Population Study in Mack Creek, Andrews Experimental Forest (Gregory, 2016). Salamander abundance (individuals) and weight (grams) were determined by annual surveys in a section of clear cut forest (ca. 1963; clear cut) and a 500-year old coniferous forest (old growth). We explored information within three channel classifications: cascades, pools, and side channels. Data collection for Pacific giant salamanders began in 1993 and is ongoing.

Changes in salamander abundance from 1993 to 2017 were explored for each forest section. Abundance was analyzed for 2017 within each channel classification using a chi-square test for independence (alpha = 0.05 throughout). We analyzed differences in mean salamander weight within each forest section using a two-sample, two-sided t-test and within channel classifications with a one-way ANOVA and post-hoc Tukeys HSD. R software (version 3.5.1) and RStudio (version 1.2.1335) were used for data analysis and figure generation.

Results

1. Salamander abundance

1a. Abundance in old growth and clear cut sections of Mack Creek

Figure 2. Pacific giant salamander abundance (1993-2017). The annual number of observations from an old growth coniferous forest (green) and a clear cut forest (brown) are shown for all years that observations were recorded.

Trends in salamander abundance between 1993 and 2017 were similar for both sections of Mack Creek. Until 2014, abundance of Pacific giant salamanders was greater in the old growth reach of Mack than in the clear cut reach. From 2015 to 2017, salamander abundance was slightly higher in the clear cut reach than the old growth reach.

1b. Abundance in different channel classifications in 2017

Table 1. Pacific giant salamander abundance for different channel classifications in 2017. Number of observations and proportions are shown for clear cut and old growth sections of Mack Creek.

Channel Classification Clear Cut Old Growth
Cascade 247 (67.1%) 201 (62.8%)
Pool 31 (8.4%) 45 (14.1%)
Side Channel 90 (24.5%) 74 (23.1%)

Salamander abundance differed among the three channel classifications. In both clear cut and old growth sections, cascades had the greatest number of salamanders (247 (67.1%) and 201 (62.8%), respectively), followed by side channels ( 90 (24.5%) and 74 (23.1%), respectively). Pools had the fewest number of salamanders for both clear cut and old growth sections ( 31 (8.4%) and 45 (14.1%), respectively).

However, there is no significant effect of forest condition (clear cut and old growth) and the channel classification (cascade, pool, or side channel) where salamanders are found (\(\chi^2\)(2) = 5.54, p = 0.063).

2. Salamander weight

2a. Weight in clear cut and old growth in 2017

We analyzed salamander weights in old growth and clear cut sections of Mack Creek for 2017. Mean salamander weight based in clear cut (7.78 0.52, mean standard error, n = 368) and old growth (6.58 0.49, n = 328) forest in 2017 did not differ significantly (two-sample, two-sided t-test, t(693) = 1.7, p = 0.096, Cohens d = 0.13).

2b. Weight in different channel classifications in 2017

We compared salamander weights in 2017 in three different channel classifications: cascades, pools, and side channels (Figure 3).

Figure 3. Pacific giant salamander weight within each channel classification in 2017. Error bars demonstrate the mean weight and standard error within each classification.

The mean weight for salamanders in side channels (5.68 0.65g, mean standard error, n = 164) was lower than for those in cascades (7.52 0.43g, n = 447) and pools (9.3 1.56, n = 76). Mean salamander weight differed significantly between the three channel classifications (one-way ANOVA F(2, 684) = 4.22, p = 0.015). Pair-wise comparisons revealed that weights varied significantly between salamanders in side channels and in pools (post-hoc Tukeys HSD, p = 0.017), but did not differ significantly between those in pools and cascades (p = 0.29) or between those in side channels and cascades (p = 0.084).

However, due to significant outliers, it is possible examining medians, rather than means, would be better for comparing salamander weights in this dataset. Alternative, non-parametric analyses such as Whitney-Mann (for two-sample analysis) and Kruskal-Wallis (for three-sample) should be explored.

Summary

  • Salamander abundance was similar for clear cut and old growth sections of Mack Creek (Figure 2)
  • In both clear cut and old growth sections, cascades had the highest abundance and pools had the lowest abundance of salamanders (Table 1).
  • Mean salamander weight in clear cut and old growth sections did not vary significantly.
  • Mean salamander weight was greatest in pools and least in side channels (Figure 3).
